'''''UFC 218: Holloway vs. Aldo 2''''' was a [[mixed martial arts]] event produced by the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] that was held on December 2, 2017, at [[Little Caesars Arena]] in [[Detroit|Detroit, Michigan]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloodyelbow.com/2017/6/26/15875518/report-ufc-late-2017-schedule-ppv-detroit-return-msg-nyc-november-mma-news|title=UFC's late 2017 schedule includes PPV in Detroit, return to MSG in November|publisher=bloodyelbow.com|author=Mookie Alexander|date=2017-06-26|access-date=2017-06-26|archive-date=2023-07-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230707162211/https://bloodyelbow.com/2017/6/26/15875518/report-ufc-late-2017-schedule-ppv-detroit-return-msg-nyc-november-mma-news|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name="Detroit">{{cite news|url=http://www.freep.com/story/sports/2017/07/30/ufc-218-detroit-little-caesars-arena/522998001/|title=Little Caesars Arena to host UFC 218 in December|publisher=freep.com|author=Christopher D. Thomas|date=2017-07-30|access-date=2017-07-30}}</ref>

==Background==
After previously contesting two events in the [[Metro Detroit]] area (and the first since [[UFC 123]] in November 2010), the event was the first for the promotion at the newly built venue.<ref name="Detroit" />

A [[UFC Featherweight Championship]] bout between current champion [[Max Holloway]] and former [[UFC Lightweight Championship|UFC Lightweight Champion]] [[Frankie Edgar]] was expected to serve as the main event.<ref name="HollowayEdgar">{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/mma/story/_/id/20909077/max-holloway-face-frankie-edgar-featherweight-title-bout-ufc-218|title=Max Holloway to put featherweight title up against Frankie Edgar|work=espn.com|author=Brett Okamoto|date=2017-10-03|access-date=2017-10-03}}</ref> However, on November 11, Edgar was forced to withdraw from the fight citing injury. He was replaced by former [[List of WEC champions#Featherweight Championship|WEC Featherweight Champion]] and former two-time champion [[José Aldo]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2017/11/11/16633192/max-holloway-vs-jose-aldo-2-slated-as-new-ufc-218-main-event|title=Max Holloway vs. Jose Aldo 2 slated as new UFC 218 main event|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Ariel Helwani|date=2017-11-11|access-date=2017-11-11}}</ref> Aldo was scheduled to face [[Ricardo Lamas]] at [[UFC on Fox: Lawler vs. dos Anjos]] in a rematch of his successful title defense at [[UFC 169]] in February, 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2017/10/jose-aldo-vs-ricardo-lamas-rematch-co-headlines-ufc-on-fox-26-perry-ponzinibbio-mein-silva-added|title=Jose Aldo vs. Ricardo Lamas rematch co-headlines UFC on FOX 26; Perry-Ponzinibbio, Mein-Silva added|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Staff|date=2017-10-13|access-date=2017-11-11}}</ref> Holloway and Aldo met previously at [[UFC 212]], with the former defeating the latter to win the championship.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2017/6/4/15736310/ufc-212-results-max-holloway-finishes-jose-aldo-claims-featherweight-crown|title=UFC 212 results: Max Holloway finishes José Aldo, claims featherweight crown|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Dave Doyle|date=2017-06-04|access-date=2017-11-11}}</ref>

A [[List of UFC Champions#Heavyweight championship|UFC Heavyweight title eliminator]] bout between former [[K-1 Grand Prix]] champion [[Alistair Overeem]] and up and coming contender [[Francis Ngannou]] co-headlined the event. The winner would be matched against champion  [[Stipe Miocic]] for the title. Miocic had previously defeated Overeem by first round [[knockout]] at [[UFC 203]] in September 2016.

A flyweight bout between [[Wrestling at the 2008 Summer Olympics – Men's freestyle 55 kg|2008 Olympic gold medalist in freestyle wrestling]] and former [[UFC Flyweight Championship]] challenger [[Henry Cejudo]] and [[Sergio Pettis]], initially scheduled for [[UFC 211]] before Cejudo pulled out with a hand injury, was rescheduled for this event.<ref name="CejudoPettis">{{cite news|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2017/9/27/16376430/henry-cejudo-vs-sergio-pettis-targeted-for-ufc-218|title=Henry Cejudo vs. Sergio Pettis targeted for UFC 218|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Ariel Helwani|date=2017-09-27|access-date=2017-09-27}}</ref> Subsequently, Cejudo's availability for the event was briefly in doubt as he suffered minor burn injuries to his right foot on the evening of October 9 as he was evacuating his hotel as a result of the [[Tubbs Fire]] near [[Santa Rosa, California]].<ref name="CejudoInjured">{{cite news|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2017/10/10/16453918/henry-cejudo-suffers-burns-loses-gold-medal-in-california-wildfire|title=Henry Cejudo suffers burns, loses gold medal in California wildfire|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Ariel Helwani|date=2017-10-10|access-date=2017-10-10}}</ref> The following day, his management team confirmed that the fight with Pettis was still on for the event.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2017/10/henry-cejudo-sergio-pettis-ufc-218-injuries-lost-olympic-medal-fire|title=Manager: Henry Cejudo will fight Sergio Pettis at UFC 218 despite injuries, lost Olympic medal in fire|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Mike Bohn|date=2017-10-10|access-date=2017-10-10}}</ref>

[[Al Iaquinta]] was scheduled to face [[Paul Felder]] at the event. However, Iaquinta pulled out of the fight on October 31 citing an injury.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2017/10/31/16586154/ufc-218-loses-paul-felder-vs-al-iaquinta|title=UFC 218 loses Paul Felder vs. Al Iaquinta|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Ariel Helwani|date=2017-10-31|access-date=2017-10-31}}</ref> Felder remained on the card against [[Charles Oliveira]].<ref name="OliveiraIn">{{cite news|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2017/10/al-iaquinta-out-charles-oliveira-in-versus-paul-felder-ufc-218|title=Al Iaquinta out, Charles Oliveira in against Paul Felder at UFC 218|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Steven Marrocco|date=2017-10-31|access-date=2017-10-31}}</ref>

